-- South African Equities: Anglo American, BHP, MTN, Telkom
-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n   a n d   J a n a   M a r a i s
-- 2012-03-30T16:12:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-03-30/south-african-equities-anglo-american-bhp-mtn-telkom.html
The  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index (JALSH) 
advanced for the first time in three days, rising 0.2 percent to
33,554.21 by the close in Johannesburg. The gauge has gained 4.9
percent this year after retreating 0.4 percent in 2011.  The following were among the most active equities in the
market today. Stock symbols follow company names.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified miner that
makes up about 9 percent of the index, climbed 0.8 percent to
285.10 rand. Standard & Poor’s  GSCI index  of commodities
rebounded from three days of losses, jumping as much as 1.2
percent.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BIL)  , the world’s biggest
resources company, advanced 0.9 percent to 233.52 rand.  MTN Group Ltd. (MTN)  ,  Africa ’s biggest mobile-phone
company, declined for a second day, dropping 1.7 percent to
135.02 rand. The company will oppose a $4.2 billion claim filed
against it by Turkcell Iletisim Hitzmetleri AS, it said after
the market closed yesterday.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG)  , Africa’s largest fixed-
line company, plunged 1.4 percent to 24 rand, its lowest level
in more than eight years, after saying earnings excluding one-
time items probably fell at least 25 percent for the year
through March.  To contact the reporters on this story:
